      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"living constitution\" theory is fundamentally a judicial philosophy that grants judges the power to interpret the law based on evolving societal norms, which is inherently political. While originalism struggles with the practical impossibility of knowing the exact intent of every Framer, the living constitution approach is often criticized for lacking objective legal constraints. Therefore, the originalist method, despite its challenges, maintains a stronger claim to legal validity because it seeks an external, historical anchor rather than an internal, subjective one.",
      "source": "target",
